Drunk on corruption.
My friend Boris was going to leave my place drunk.
I suggested to him therefore not to drive.
He asked me why.
"You have drunk," I told him, "haven't you got afraid of the police?"
Boris replied to me : "no, I have a document with Benjamin Franklin's likeness, it always comes in handy".
He showed me his driver's license with the $100 bill slipped beside it.
Obviously, I knew that the police were taking bribes, but I worried that Boris would meet a policeman who wasn't corrupt.
"It's impossible", Boris said, "to join the traffic police force, you have to buy your boss's silence."
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy the silence of your boss ?
Half of Moscow's drivers use illegally purchased driving licenses.
Fools who try to do things by the book are drowning in bureaucratic red tape.
For a hundred dollars, you can drive in the city without brakes !
Corruption and embezzlement of funds have always existed in Russia, both before and after Lenin's October Revolution.
But never at record levels we see today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for everything.
Only those to whom it is not offered accept it, according to Boris.
Corruption thrives in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a catastrophe or abandonment.
No one anywhere is immunized.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of the most beautiful Moscow suburbs.
It was a luxurious place but similar to the gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Examing the pretentious and tastelessly decorated houses, I asked who owned them and heard that one belonged to an assistant to the mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and another to the son of the Moscow prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest official from the tax office.
Corruption now represents a more serious threat to Russia than the Chechen War.
In fact, the Chechen War would not have lasted as long if it were not led by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police officers who sell arms and supplies to the rebels.
Recently, Russian television showed a bus making shuttle runs from Grozny to Moscow, the same bus that brought 120 kilograms of explosives used in the Dubrovka Theatre Siege, where so many victims perished during the assault intended to free the hostages.
A bus passenger covered the explosives with a rag soaked in acid to prevent customs dogs from detecting them.
A completely unnecessary precaution.
No one controls the buses anymore today.
The driver who didn't know what he was transporting said he was stopped 50 times along his route, and always for the same thing.
A police officer came to ask him: "do you know the price?", and the driver replied: "of course, I know it", while paying the bribe before leaving.
Without bribes, the bus would have been delayed for hours at every stop, or entire days for the journey.
The war against Chechnya continues indefinitely not only because Chechen rebels have allies like Al Qaïda and all "the international terrorist community" but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes, and thieves, who first tax Chechen civilians or simply steal from them, sell arms and explosives to terrorists, maps showing where landmines are located, and provide rebels with fake documents.
In May of this year, during the Kaspiisk explosions, the terrorists used arms bought from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from ?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no gunsmith shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels, however, have their own ammunition stocks, from which the guns are stolen and sold.
And not just the guns: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, yet no fight has been launched against this plague.
Punishing corruption more harshly ?
This would only increase the prices of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more you'll have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they are corrupted themselves.
So, those referred to as "simple people" view this phenomenon with benevolence.
They say of their mayor "yes, he steals, but look at everything he's done for the city!"
Ordinary people don't like honest workers either.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, you can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the controller both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother told me one day that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The conductor had stopped her by telling her that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on the train.
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up to serve in the army, buy a military clerk and he will erase your son's name from the list, or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any faculty for a certain price, no matter your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed recklessly, run red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is around to offer himself to the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When Tsar Peter disgusted by the corruption of Russia decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
In the centuries that have passed since, the situation has worsened.
Eradicating corruption might well leave the state without citizens, but if we don't stop the spread of corruption, citizens will soon be left without a state.
